<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-486-558  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 486 558.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer-Aided Engineering  July 1989 v8 n7 p129(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Solving the factory automation paradox.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>St. Charles, David P.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The use of a simultaneous engineering approach to the design ofproducts and product manufacturing technology, while consideringcommunications and people involved in the entire product cyclewill optimize the performance and cost benefits of manufacturingautomation.andP;  90 percent of product costs are locked in at thedesign stage, but American manufacturers have been losing marketground to foreign competitors because the US firms haveconcentrated on automating 'touch labor,' which represents no morethan 15 percent of product costs.andP;  A simultaneous engineeringprocess will involve design, manufacturing, and quality engineers,as well as marketing and sales personnel from the beginning,enabling designers to understand the manufacturing and marketrequirements.andP;  Product design should reflect those requirements,resulting in a faster, less expensive, and more reliable designprocess.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     AutomationPerformance ImprovementUnited StatesTutorialProduct DevelopmentSystem DesignIntegrated ApproachManufacturing.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>